\subsection{2. $\mathrm{V}$ and $4 \mathrm{~d} \mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ Co-Doping (Mo, Tc, Ru and Pd)}
As shown in Figure 6, the IELs introduced by V-4d $\mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ co-doping emerges in the middle of bandgap and CB. Compared with Figure 4 , the IELs of the $4 \mathrm{~d}$ metals are even closer to the CB than the IELs of $3 d$ metals. The reason is that the $4 \mathrm{~d}$ states have higher energy than the $3 d$ states of the transition metals. Therefore, the IELs of V co-doping with the $4 \mathrm{~d}$ transition metals are closer to the conduction band and belong to the significant n-doping. The Fermi level (EF) gradually shifts from the conduction band to the valence band with the increase of the atomic number of the $\mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ elements. The definition of the Fermi level is the highest energy level of the electron at the absolute zero degree, which corresponds to the energy state at $0 \mathrm{eV}$. It can act as a reference to discuss the effects of the transition metal co-doping on the band edge modification and the bandgap variation. The IELs in the bandgap and near the bottom of the CB partially (V-Tc, V-Ru and V-Pd co-doping systems) or wholly overlap with the CBM (V-Mo co-doping system). Both cases can lead to the CBM downward shifting, while the valence bands remain barely unchanged upon the co-doping. The Fermi levels of the V-M" (Mo, Tc, Ru and Pd) co-doping systems pass through the IELs, that is to say, the electrons can occupy the IELs below the Fermi level in the ground state. Due to the small distance between this energy level and the bottom of the CB, electrons can be excited by absorbing small photon energy [46,47].

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth]{2023_09_22_63a752c620bbc784200cg-07_1102_2084_311_1756}
\end{center}

Figure 6. The total and partial density of states of the V-M" (4d metal elements: Mo, Tc, Ru and Pd) co-doped $\mathrm{BaTiO}_{3}$. The black dashed line indicates the position of the Fermi level.

\subsection{3. $\mathrm{Nb}$ and $3 \mathrm{~d} \mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime} \mathrm{Co}$-Doping (Cr, Mn, Fe, Co and Ni)}
Figure 7 shows that the effects of this series of co-doping are similar to the V-M ${ }^{\prime \prime}(\mathrm{Cr}, \mathrm{Mn}, \mathrm{Fe}, \mathrm{Co}$ and Ni) co-doping described in Figure 4 . The only difference is that the energy of the Nb $4 \mathrm{~d}$ states is higher than that of the V 3 d states. Consequently, the V 3 d states are located at the CBM but the Nb $4 d$ states are in the upper $\mathrm{CB}$. Therefore, the $\mathrm{Nb} 4 \mathrm{~d}$ states have little effect on the bandgap and there is no synergistic effect between the co-dopants. The Fermi level moves from CB to VB with the increase of the atomic number of $\mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ elements. The $\mathrm{Cr}, \mathrm{Mn}$, and Ni 3 d states occur in the middle of the bandgap and become the intermediate level. The intermediate state might be beneficial to the electron transition under visible-light irradiation. However, it might not be conducive to the effective separation of the electron-hole since it could also act as the recombination centers on the other hand. In addition, the Fe and Co 3d states are divided into two parts, where the high energy part is weak at the bottom of the CB, and the low energy part is strong, which is located at the top of the VB. Both cases can lead to the bandgap narrowing and are beneficial to visible-light absorption.

In these $\mathrm{Nb}-\mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ co-doping systems, we chose two typical doping forms, the $\mathrm{Nb}-\mathrm{Mn}$ and $\mathrm{Nb}-\mathrm{Co}$ co-doping systems, to further investigate their band structures, as shown in Figure 8 . The bandgaps are found to be $1.2$ and $0.96 \mathrm{eV}$, respectively. In the Nb-Mn co-doping system, the IELs in the middle of bandgap are contributed by the Mn $3 d$ states. However, in the $\mathrm{Nb}$ and $\mathrm{Co}$ co-doping system, the Co $3 \mathrm{~d}$ and $\mathrm{O} 2 \mathrm{p}$ states form the $\mathrm{p}$ - $\mathrm{d}$ hybridization and locate above the original VB or partly coincided with the bottom of the CB. Overall, both co-doping could reduce the bandgap effectively but with different causes. It is also necessary to consider that $\mathrm{Nb}$ and $\mathrm{Mn}$ heavy co-doping might lead to a serious recombination due to the IELs in the bandgap.

