\section{Conclusions}
In summary, the formation energy and electronic properties of the transition metal V-M $\mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ and $\mathrm{Nb}^{\prime \prime} \mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ co-doped $\mathrm{BaTiO}_{3}$ have been studied by first-principles calculations. The results indicate that the $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ co-doping is more suitable than the $\mathrm{Nb}^{\prime \prime} \mathrm{M}^{\prime \prime}$ co-doping for narrowing the bandgap of BaTiO ${ }_{3}$

\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth, center]{2023_09_22_63a752c620bbc784200cg-12_1839_1890_254_1808}\\
around the bandgap edge while those energy levels induced by the Nb-M ${ }^{\prime \prime}$ co-doping are usually deep levels in the energy band or bandgap. The optimal co-doping model is proposed as the $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{Cr}$ co-doped $\mathrm{BaTiO}_{3}$, which not only has favorable defect formation energy, but also significantly reduce the bandgap. Simultaneous introduction of $\mathrm{V}$ and $\mathrm{Cr}$ results in a synergistic effect, which has been demonstrated by the detailed analysis of the density of states, band structure, and charge-density distribution of the doping systems. $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{Cr}$ co-doping could overcome the shortcoming of the single $\mathrm{Cr}$ doping and combine the advantages of both the $\mathrm{V}$ and $\mathrm{Cr}$ doping. For this optimal co-doped $\mathrm{BaTiO}_{3}$ system, the Cr $3 d$ states are located just above the VBM and the V $3 d$ states occupied band just below the CBM, corresponding to a bandgap narrowing of about $0.4 \mathrm{eV}$, which is beneficial for efficient visible-light adsorption. The results can provide an important guideline for future experiments to modify the wide $\mathrm{BaTiO}_{3}$ bandgap for visible-light driven solar applications.

